	voicesCreditHtml={`Photos via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Wikimedia Commons</a> &mdash; George MacDonald, Charles Spurgeon, and Martin Luther (all public domain).`}
	wordHeading={`His Word will not return void`}
	wordBodyHtml={`<p>When our Father said, “Let there be light,” there was light. His Word does what He sends it to do. The same Word you sing in a children’s song and act out with a felt board will not come back empty — not in the child who seems distracted, and not in <em>you</em>.</p><p class=\\"mt-4\\" style=\\"color: var(--color-ink);\\">“My word… will not return to me empty, but will accomplish that which I purpose.” <span style=\\"color: var(--color-muted);\\">— Isaiah 55:11</span></p>`}
	fatherSaysHeading={`What the Father says over you`}
	fatherSaysHtml={`<p>“Beloved, before you ever taught a child about Me, I was teaching you that you are Mine. You are not My helper; you are My child. I see every Sunday no one else sees — every tear you wiped, every name you learned, every prayer you whispered over a wiggling little one. None of it is small to Me.</p><p>Put down the weight of the empty volunteer slot for a moment. You do not have to be enough; you only have to come to Me and be filled. Let Me gather you in My arms the way you gather the lambs. Let Me father you. Then go and love them — not to earn the delight I already have over you, but because you are loved, and the love simply overflows onto the next generation. I am your Father, and you are Mine.”`}
	prayerHeading={`A prayer for children’s ministry`}
	prayerHtml={`<p>Our Father, we thank You and praise You for all who serve in children’s ministry — the ones who pour into the youngest and the unseen, who plant seeds they may never watch bloom, who keep showing up in the nursery and the classroom while the world looks the other way. Let them hear Your whisper above the noise of recruiting, shortage, and tired Sundays. Let them encounter Your love — not as a lesson they teach, but as a weight they feel — and experience Your delight over them, apart from any headcount, any thank-you, any outcome they can measure.</p><p>Give them grace to prioritize intimacy with You above their serving, and to receive their identity as Your sons and daughters before their role as teachers and helpers. Father, gather these carriers of children into Your own arms and carry them; let them be fathered before they ever disciple another child, and let the love they receive from You pour straight onto the next generation.</p><p>I pray Your protection over them from the enemy, from temptation, from discouragement and the lie that their hidden work is small, and from despair. Let them know there is no condemnation in You. Let them know You, their Father, as their true inheritance and reward, for every other gift pales beside the gift of You. And may they wake up every single day under the pour of their heavenly Father’s heart for them.</p><p>In Jesus’ name, amen.</p>`}
